<style>

div.left_top_fixed {
  position: fixed;
  bottom: 1;
  right: 1;
  width: 300px;
  border: 4px solid green;
  font-size: 30px;
}


div.right_top_fixed {
  position: fixed;
  bottom: 1;
  right: 0;
  width: 300px;
  border: 4px solid blue;
  font-size: 30px;
}

div.right_botttom_fixed {
  position: fixed;
  bottom: 0;
  right: 0;
  width: 300px;
  border: 4px solid #FF0000;
  font-size: 30px;
}

div.left_bottom_fixed {
  position: fixed;
  bottom: 0;
  right: 1;
  width: 300px;
  border: 4px solid #800080;
  font-size: 30px;
}
</style>


</head>

<body bgcolor = "#BCE954">

<div class="left_top_fixed">
This div element is at right:1 bottom:1;
</div>

<div class="right_top_fixed">
This div element is at right:0 bottom:1;
</div>

<h3>An element with position: fixed; is positioned relative to the viewport, which means it always stays in the same place even if the page is scrolled:</h3>


<h3>Right and bottom attributes function like poles because it only places things in the corners, for example  'right:0' and 'right:1' is absolute left.



<h3>Cannot go past the container, so 'right:1000' in the body still wont break into the header </h3>

<div class="left_bottom_fixed">
This div element is at right:1 bottom:0;
</div>


<div class="right_botttom_fixed">
This div element is at right:0 bottom:0;
</div>




</body>


